label chapter11:

    # [Scene: Glasshouse Lab & Seedbank | Late Afternoon — after an eventful day]

    scene bg ch11_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A taut, staccato string ostinato; heartbeat-synced.]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft, mechanical hum of pumps. Outside: distant voices and the low rumble of a crowd.]
    "You come in carrying whatever weight the day allowed you to keep — a satchel half-full of flyers, a phone with its battery tags of missed calls, the buoy pendant cold against your sternum. Whether you"
    "walked back from the lanterns of the festival or from the fluorescent hush of the municipal hall, you arrive to instruments that do not sleep: sensors pulsing, a laptop with a live feed, a printer that"
    "keeps spitting out strips of plotted lines."
    "The air in the glasshouse is humid and smells of wet peat and old paper. Your hands still smell faintly of smoke and kelp oil; someone — Mika, probably — has left a mug with half"
    "a cigarette's worth of ash and the residue of instant coffee on the bench. Every small domestic detail is a proof that life continues; every proof feels like an accusation."
    show mika_tran at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mika_tran "You're late. The feed's been flaring for an hour.' (She taps the laptop with a stylus like a conductor's baton.) 'We kept the readings going the whole time. Folks wanted numbers they could hold."
    show marina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "And they had them."
    "Mika's mouth tightens; she leans over the screen, eyes wide with the kind of tired that doesn't sleep because there's always one more sensor to check. Data runs along the axis: elevations, recurrence intervals, a red smear that keeps pulsing. You know that smear as well as your own bruises."
    show amalia_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amalia_reyes "Some of them took it well, some didn't.' (She folds and refolds a flyer with dry hands.) 'And—"
    "You want to ask whether the festival crowd calmed or whether the council meeting stayed behind closed doors and negotiated quietly. You want to ask whether the projections you carried were shown under fairy lights or"
    "under the municipal seal. But you can't — you don't know where this conversation will be true for every version of you that arrived here. The question is a knife-edge between accusations and absolution; you pivot"
    "instead to what's in front of you."

    marina_reyes "What did the people do? Not the numbers — the people."
    "Amalia looks at you like you just asked for the moon to be rewired. 'Some ran,' she says. 'Some called lawyers. Old Tom—'"
    "Old Tom's footsteps scrape as he comes in, rain on his coat, salt in his voice. He looks smaller than he used to, daylight having eaten some of the broadness from his shoulders, but the bead of anger in his face is old and familiar."
    hide mika_tran
    show thomas_old_tom_bellamy at left:
        zoom 0.7

    thomas_old_tom_bellamy "You put charts where a man's memory used to stand.' (There is a long pause as everyone inhales around this.) 'I respect what you're trying to do — I do — but you make the past tidy and the future cruel."
    "You feel the air go electric: a current that isn't just from the pumps. Old Tom's words land like stones in a still pool and send ripples into every conversation you've had this week."
    "Elias Kato stands at the doorway. His trench is damp at the hem; the wet makes it look heavier, as if the weather itself is a verdict on the choices he's carried. He looks at the"
    "printed lines and at you, and for a moment his face is unreadable — complex in the way of tide marks. He folds his arms and then unfolds them, like someone working a calculation into acceptance."
    hide marina_reyes
    show elias_kato at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kato "We got what we needed out of the meeting, in the way meetings give you things.' (He looks down at the stacks of paper, then at Mika.) 'Not everything we wanted. Not everything that should be done."
    hide amalia_reyes
    show marina_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "Did we win anything at all?"
    "Elias Kato's throat works. He runs a hand through his hair and the gesture is so small you almost miss it — an attempt at normalcy in a room that refuses it."

    elias_kato "We bought bridges. Not the sort that keep everyone. The sort that let some cross."
    "His words are clipped like a draft through a half-closed window. The lab's warmth feels suddenly like an oven; the humidity thickens into a pressure that settles into your lungs."

    menu:
        "Quietly archive the raw data tonight, limit public panic":
            "You send the raw files to a secure folder and mark them confidential. It eases the immediate fray — phone calls slow, the lab's shoulders drop — but the ache in your chest grows; truth sealed feels like burying a compass."
        "Broadcast the live feed to the town's channel":
            "You press send and watch the stream crawl out into the night. Comments explode: some grateful, some furious, some begging. The feed ripples like spilled oil — visibility gives people agency, but it also detonates fear."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    "You make a small decision — one that in some versions of the day you have already made, and in others you still might. The lab holds its breath like a lung bracing for a storm."
    # [Scene: Reclaimed Wetlands Festival / Night Market | Twilight — simultaneous flashpoint]
    hide thomas_old_tom_bellamy
    hide elias_kato
    hide marina_reyes

    scene bg ch11_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive, urgent. Distant thunder.]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A rising murmur that turns into shouts. Chairs scraping. A child's cry.]
    "The instruments at the festival — or the same instruments that have just been carried into a municipal evidence binder — behave like witnesses. They do not lie. They sing in voltages and red lines."

    "Old Tom stands under a paper lantern, its light trembling over his face. Next to him, a neighbor argues with a man from the construction crew about the height of a seawall and the price of a moving truck with the same sharpness. Two women start whispering and their whisper swells into a chant" "Our houses, our houses."
    "Amalia moves through the crowd like a tide-breaker, her clipboard returning to its job of bearing names and needs. She approaches you, eyes rimmed with the salt of unshed tears, and speaks fast."
    show amalia_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amalia_reyes "They're split. Half want to start boarding things up tonight. Half want assurance — a number, a plan. Old Tom won't budge, some councilpeople are already offering spaces in the school gym. He says he'll die in the house before he leaves."
    "You feel the room tilt. Someone laughs when it should be weeping; someone cries when it should be quiet. The town is not a single organism tonight — it's a collection of living things lashing out to survive."
    "A woman in the front — a farmer with salt-stiff hair — points at the upturned map on the display. 'If those maps are right,' she says, voice thin as a twig, 'they took our summer. Took our kids' beds.'"
    "A rough hand grips your shoulder; Elias Kato is there without sound the way a storm is present without permission. He looks at you as if testing the temperature of your pulse."
    show elias_kato at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kato "We can set up the kelp pilots where they'll help the most. Small wins. It won't save everyone, but—' (He stops because you know the rest.) 'We can anchor the most vulnerable places. We can buy breathing room."
    show marina_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "Buy breathing room for whom, Elias? Who decides who gets to breathe?"
    "Elias Kato's jaw tightens. He looks away, at the live feed scrolling comments in a language of panic and prayer. He tries to make numbers into mercy and mercy into policy, and the conversion breaks somewhere between a spreadsheet and a human throat."

    elias_kato "We decide, together. We listen.' (He meets your eyes.) 'We do the best with what we can keep."
    "But the best is a knife-edge. The crowd grows ragged; a shout turns into a scuffle. Someone pushes a young man back from a table of petitions. Old Tom's cane smacks a board and the sound cracks like a pistol."
    hide amalia_reyes
    show thomas_old_tom_bellamy at left:
        zoom 0.7

    thomas_old_tom_bellamy "You who talk of 'together' — listen to me. I remember a season when the sea took more than it returned. I'm not moving because a chart tells me I should. I'm staying because this is the last place that remembers my wife's laugh."
    "Silence fractures into sobbing. The festival's warm bulbs feel suddenly like bulbs above a stage where the town performs its grief."

    menu:
        "Step between them and speak from the lab's readings":
            "You lift your hands and let the data speak as if it were a human: slow, patient, translated into stories of basements and fish stocks and children. Some faces soften; others harden with accusation."
        "Let the crowd rage; save your strength for negotiations":
            "You step back and let people speak their fury. The noise is therapeutic and cruel; it frees them and forces you to tend the wounds later. You feel the sting of choosing when to intervene."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    "The instruments keep telling a truth that is not the only truth. Numbers do not comfort when the shoreline looks like memory and the council offers packets."
    # [Scene: Municipal Hall | Night — the thin geometry of compromise]
    hide elias_kato
    hide marina_reyes
    hide thomas_old_tom_bellamy

    scene bg ch11_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, claustrophobic cello drones. Pulsing high strings like a siren in the distance.]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Muffled shouting outside the windows. Papers shuffled like an attempt to cover a wound.]
    "If the data were released publicly at the festival, tonight is the stretch of wakefulness after the explosion. If the projections were kept confidential and the council met behind closed doors, tonight is the brittle calm"
    "after those negotiations. Both versions end up in this room: a place of leases and forms and the soft, practiced cruelty of policy."
    show rina_corbett at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rina_corbett "We have funds — not enough, but something. Targeted relocation with support. Short-term shelters. A pilot grant for community labs.' (She taps a legal pad where the words are precise and terrible.) 'But the politics will only let us take so much land off the map without the whole council signing."
    show marina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "Who signs? Who stays?"
    "Rina's eyes are a machine of calculation with human wear. 'Some will be offered buyouts. Some will be offered infrastructure. We can protect the school and the clinic. The rest — we try to move to safer ground with help.'"
    show amalia_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amalia_reyes "You're promising me a floor in a gym for Old Tom?"

    rina_corbett "Temporary housing. Counseling. Retraining. We can make transitions less violent."

    marina_reyes "Temporary for who? Temporary until what?"
    "The debate rocks between humane language and the bluntness of budget lines. You watch the town split itself into math and memory. The puzzle pieces are faces and addresses."
    "Elias Kato sits beside you at the table. He has a pen and lets it roll in his fingers, a small, measured motion. He says nothing for a long moment, and then he says what practical people say when the room shrinks to numbers."
    hide rina_corbett
    show elias_kato at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kato "We can't save everything the way we want. We can save some things in a way that preserves dignity. If we don't act, we'll lose more by chaos."
    "You want to ask whether dignity is a currency that buys housing, whether it can be tallied. You want to ask whether his 'we' includes the people who refuse to be moved, but the night is an assembly of compromises that smell faintly of ash."
    "Somewhere — at the periphery, in a corridor where the fluorescent light hums like a wasp — a table is overturned. Voices spill out. A woman cries that her father will not leave, and she punches"
    "a filing cabinet in a grief that is more honest than any negotiation. You feel your chest hollower on one side as if you have lost a tool you didn't realize you held."
    "Mika stands and paces. Her youthful hands tremble. 'We have the sensors,' she says. 'We get the pilot grant, we can start now in the spots people will actually use. But the optics — the optics will eat us. People will call us the reason their houses are marked.'"

    marina_reyes "What do we do, Mika?"
    "Mika's answer is a quiet thing, a furnace barely lit. 'We fix what we can. We stay with our people. We watch them leave. We make sure that when someone has to go, they don't go alone.'"
    "You are an anchor and also a blade. The cooperative — the long-lines of kelp, the tiny labs in converted sheds — gets tenser support than you hoped. Funding arrives in an envelope that smells like"
    "bureaucracy and hope. It is both a rescue and a bandage. The town gives a little; the council keeps most; the sea keeps the rest."
    "Old Tom is in the hallway when you come out. He grips you like he grips his cane, with surprising force and the heat of accusation still in his palms."
    hide marina_reyes
    show thomas_old_tom_bellamy at right:
        zoom 0.7

    thomas_old_tom_bellamy "You did what you could, Marina. My wife would be proud. And also damned, for making the sea a ledger.' (He leans in so close you can hear the rasp of his breath.) 'You promised a line to keep us. Did you know lines can cut?"
    "You stand with the echo of that question ringing in your bones. The lab's pump hums in your ears like a threatened heart. The ache in your chest blooms wide and black."
    "Elias Kato reaches for your hand but stops midair, a habitual tenderness barred by the shape of the night's choices. His hand rests near yours and then drops, the unreadability curling into something that looks like grief."

    elias_kato "I can't make this un-happen. I won't pretend otherwise.' (He looks at you with a steadiness that is now worn thin.) 'I'll be there. Quietly. Complicatedly. I won't make promises I can't keep."
    hide amalia_reyes
    show marina_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "Will you stay?"

    "He doesn't answer directly. Instead, he says the only thing his profession has made elegant" "I'll keep the channels open. I'll keep a seat at the table. Where we stand will be measured in small, practical things."
    "You feel like the world is no longer a map but a series of lit rooms where people make unbearable decisions. The cooperative draws a thin, frayed line of funding. Political victory, if it exists at"
    "all tonight, is a letter in an envelope. Social fabric has been stretched so thin you can see the threads; some snap."
    "Your chest is a drum of panic and a slow, cold grief."

    menu:
        "Go back to the flats and start the pilot tonight":
            "You grab your satchel and the small kit of spores and head into the wind. The decision is action dressed as defiance. The sea smells like salt and threat; the work will be dangerous, and it will mean leaving people behind to paperwork."
        "Stay and help coordinate relocation logistics":
            "You stay in the municipal light and move through forms and phone lists. You feel bureaucratic, useful, and hollow; each signature you shepherd carries the weight of a home evacuated."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    "You feel the escalation in every bone: from the festival's panic to the hall's measured cruelty, to the lab's private grief. The town undulates between hope and fracture; someone gains shelter, someone loses a shore. The"
    "cooperative may survive in a small, aching way — a seed that risked a soil of conflict — but tonight that survival tastes like ash."
    "The instruments in the lab keep beeping. There is a final, impossible sound outside: the sea against pilings, a percussive, urgent banging that says the night is not done with you yet."
    "You step to the doorway — or you imagine stepping, depending on which version of the day you inhabit — and the wind takes your hair like an accusation. Your fingers close around the buoy pendant at your throat as if it were a lifeline."
    "You realize, with a cold absolute clarity that sharpens terror into resolve: whatever small victories you have will be bought in human cost. The town will be different tomorrow, and not all of that difference will"
    "be for the better. You have a choice — or you are about to make one in the quiet after the noise — and whatever you choose will ripple outward."
    "The night presses in. The pumps in the glasshouse clack like teeth."
    "You look at the sacks of spores in your satchel, at the lines you could anchor, at the faces you cannot fix. Somewhere, someone is already choosing a future you didn't want to ask them to choose."
    "You feel the arousal of panic tighten into the moment where action must be defined."
    "You inhale. The air tastes of iron and seaweed and old paper."
    "You turn your face to the flats, toward the dark line where water and land argue."
    "A single thought lifts, small and seedlike: to plant is to promise something will grow; to promise is to risk that it will not."
    # [Page-Turn Moment: The buoy pendant is warm under your fingers. You have plans, and you have losses. You realize that the first real test of the cooperative won't be charts or grants, but the simple, brutal labor of standing with neighbors while decisions are made around them. You whisper a name — a list, a vow, a litany — and the wind snatches it into the night.]
